{"id":"2302.01841","submitter":"Francesco Ardizzon","authors":"Laura Crosara, Francesco Ardizzon, Stefano Tomasin, and Nicola\n  Laurenti","title":"On the Optimal Spoofing Attack and Countermeasure in Satellite\n  Navigation Systems","comments":"Submitted to TIFS","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  The threat of signal spoofing attacks against GNSS has grown in recent years\nand has motivated the study of anti-spoofing techniques. However, defense\nmethods have been designed only against specific attacks. This paper introduces\na general model of the spoofing attack framework in GNSS, from which optimal\nattack and defense strategies are derived. We consider a scenario with a\nlegitimate receiver (Bob) testing if the received signals come from multiple\nlegitimate space vehicles (Alice) or from an attack device (Eve). We first\nderive the optimal attack strategy against a Gaussian transmission from Alice,\nby minimizing an outer bound on the achievable error probability region of the\nspoofing detection test. Then, framing the spoofing and its detection as an\nadversarial game, we show that the Gaussian transmission and the corresponding\noptimal attack constitute a Nash equilibrium. Lastly, we consider the case of\npractical modulation schemes for Alice and derive the generalized likelihood\nratio test. Numerical results validate the analytical derivations and show that\nthe bound on the achievable error region is representative of the actual\nperformance.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 3 Feb 2023 16:33:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-06"}
