{"id":"2302.02186","submitter":"Shivam Bajaj","authors":"Shivam Bajaj, Shaunak D. Bopardikar, Alexander Von Moll, Eric Torng,\n  and David W. Casbeer","title":"Perimeter Defense using a Turret with Finite Range and Service Times","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SY cs.SY","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  We consider a perimeter defense problem in a planar conical environment\ncomprising a single turret that has a finite range and non-zero service time.\nThe turret seeks to defend a concentric perimeter against $N\\geq 2$ intruders.\nUpon release, each intruder moves radially towards the perimeter with a fixed\nspeed. To capture an intruder, the turret's angle must be aligned with that of\nthe intruder's angle and must spend a specified service time at that\norientation. We address offline and online versions of this optimization\nproblem. Specifically, in the offline version, we establish that in general\nparameter regimes, this problem is equivalent to solving a Travelling\nRepairperson Problem with Time Windows (TRP-TW). We then identify specific\nparameter regimes in which there is a polynomial time algorithm that maximizes\nthe number of intruders captured. In the online version, we present a\ncompetitive analysis technique in which we establish a fundamental guarantee on\nthe existence of at best $(N-1)$-competitive algorithms. We also design two\nonline algorithms that are provably $1$ and $2$-competitive in specific\nparameter regimes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 4 Feb 2023 15:45:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-07"}
